[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"im working on case studies for clarityapp.com financial aid packages. please create an ai agent that can optimize the financial aid offered based on the parent's financial scenario understanding there are typical financial aid questions gathered for clarity to process the financial aid application. clarity asks for 2023 and 2024 tax return income, household expenses, any other sources of income and assets, and the amount the family is able to pay? are there any existing websites that let you simulate real financial aid case studies or scenarios without submitting the actual application to clarity app? Financial Aid Calculator - Invest529 https://www.invest529.com/resources/financial-aid-calculator/ Financial Aid Calculator for Private Schools - ThoughtCo https://www.thoughtco.com/private-schools-determine-financial-aid-2774005 Federal Student Aid Estimator https://studentaid.gov/aid-estimator/ 26 sources Online Financial Aid Simulators and Calculators for Private and College Financial Aid Several websites offer online calculators or estimators that allow families to simulate or model their potential financial aid scenarios, including inputs such as recent tax year income, household expenses, other income, assets, and estimation of Expected Family Contribution (EFC) or Student Aid Index (SAI). FinAid.org SAI and EFC Calculators: FinAid.org provides both a Student Aid Index (SAI) calculator and an Expected Family Contribution (EFC) calculator. These tools allow you to input detailed information, such as income (from recent tax return years), assets, and some family expense data, and then estimate your eligibility for need-based aid or what colleges might expect your family to contribute519. SavingForCollege.com Financial Aid Calculator: This calculator supports inputs for 2025-2026 aid year and allows you to enter your income and asset data to estimate your SAI, which realistically models your federal need-based financial aid eligibility20. Get2College SAI Calculator: Another tool providing user-friendly input fields for household circumstances and income, generating an instant estimate for what a college would expect your family to contribute22. Federal Student Aid Estimator (studentaid.gov): For college financial aid, this government tool estimates the amount of federal student aid you might receive using financial information similar to that required on the FAFSA, including tax return years and family composition3. NAIS Sample Aid Calculations: The National Association of Independent Schools (NAIS) provides sample aid calculation scenarios, helping families understand the methodology though it lacks interactive input fields8. Limitations Compared to Clarity While some private K–12 school calculators (such as those using SSS or FACTS) are available, most scenario-based modeling for private K–12 financial aid is embedded within application systems, like Clarity or SSS, and typically requires an actual application. The estimators listed above often model the process for colleges using FAFSA or CSS Profile criteria, but their logic is similar for basic need analysis regarding income, assets, household size, and educational costs2520. Examples of Use These estimator tools are intended for planning and informational purposes only. None require a submission to or creation of an account with Clarity. For private school, tools like the NAIS sample calculations or SAI calculator on FinAid.org provide helpful modeling for potential family obligations. For college aid, the Federal Student Aid Estimator and associated calculators provide robust scenario analysis without application submission. These tools enable users to model a variety of scenarios using household financial data, supporting informed decisions about affordability and financial aid strategies. Additional resources exist specifically for private K–12 school families seeking scenario modeling: Many private K–12 schools use platforms like SSS (School and Student Services) and FACTS Management, both of which offer online grant and aid estimators. However, most require at least limited personal information submission to view a simulation, though not a full application26. Some schools, such as The Hotchkiss School, have dedicated online financial aid estimators for the 2024-25 year that allow families to enter information similar to tax return income, assets, and basic expenses, yielding a quick snapshot of estimated family obligation4. Invest529 offers a financial aid calculator that can estimate your family's Student Aid Index (SAI) and potential eligibility for aid, also supporting inputs about income, assets, and other relevant data1. For those looking to simulate private school affordability more generally, sources such as Sourcetable feature private school affordability calculators. These focus primarily on expected budgets versus tuition and sometimes allow for customization of input data, including family income and expenses7. Regarding the ThoughtCo overview, it's important to note there is no fool-proof, universally recognized private K–12 financial aid calculator as each school sets its own aid methodology. However, the methodologies are typically transparent in what is requested (income, assets, expenses, family size, etc.), and many schools will provide statistics upon request, such as percent of need met or average aid package, to help model potential scenarios2. Some calculators now reference the recent transition from \"Expected Family Contribution (EFC)\" to the new \"Student Aid Index (SAI)\", which functions similarly but is intended to clarify that the number is an index, not a direct bill. Many calculators have updated language to reflect this change, but the fundamental inputs and method remain the same79. Mind Map Expand FinAid.org SAI and EFC Calculators SavingForCollege.com Financial Aid Calculator Get2College SAI Calculator Federal Student Aid Estimator NAIS Sample Aid Calculations Financial Aid Calculators K–12 school calculators embedded in systems Models often based on FAFSA/CSS criteria Limitations Compared to Clarity Tools for planning and information only Private school calculators like FinAid.org College aid estimators for analysis Examples of Use Schools using SSS and FACTS Management Invest529 financial aid calculator Sourcetable private school affordability calculators Additional Resources for K–12 Families No universally recognized K–12 calculator Methodologies usually transparent Transition from EFC to SAI Important Considerations Online Financial Aid Simulators and Calculators How do private K-12 school financial aid formulas differ from college calculators? What inputs affect the Student Aid Index (SAI) the most in financial aid simulators? How accurate are private school financial aid estimators compared to actual award letters? What inputs affect the Student Aid Index (SAI) the most in financial aid simulators? Federal Student Aid Estimator https://studentaid.gov/aid-estimator/ Student Aid Index (SAI) Calculator - FinAid.org https://finaid.org/calculators/saicalculator/ What is the Student Aid Index (SAI)? - MEFA https://www.mefa.org/article/what-is-the-student-aid-index-sai/ 24 sources The Student Aid Index (SAI) is a key metric used by US colleges and private schools to determine a student's eligibility for need-based financial aid. The most influential inputs or factors commonly used in SAI calculators and simulators include: Family income: Both the parent's (if dependent) and student's (if independent or applicable) income—specifically Adjusted Gross Income as reported on tax returns—play a central role in SAI calculation61018. Family assets: The net worth of parents' and (if applicable) students' assets, including savings, investment accounts, and other financial resources, are factored in after certain protections and exclusions681023. Family size and number in college: The number of people in the household and how many are attending college at least half-time influence how much the family is reasonably expected to contribute810. Parents' marital status: Whether parents are married, separated, divorced, or remarried (and household composition) can affect which incomes and assets are included in the formula8. State of residence: Some calculators make minor adjustments based on the family’s state of residence, which can influence cost of living allowances8. Student income and assets: Any income or assets in the student's name are assessed, with student assets and income typically weighed more heavily than parents’823. These are the primary drivers in federal financial aid calculations. Some private colleges, especially those using the CSS Profile, may consider home equity, non-custodial parent assets, and certain expenses as additional factors, but for federal SAI and simulators, the above list reflects the most decisive elements1081823. A few critical details and recent changes to the SAI calculation should be highlighted for clarity and completeness: The SAI replaced the former Expected Family Contribution (EFC) starting with the 2024–25 FAFSA; the term “number in college” is now less influential because, unlike the old EFC formula, the SAI does NOT divide the parent portion by the number of dependent children in college at the same time. This change means families with multiple students in college at once may see reduced eligibility for need-based aid compared to the previous EFC system8. New rules require families to include the net worth of family-owned small businesses and family farms in their reported assets. Previously, these could be excluded; now, unless the primary residence and the business are on the same deed, these assets are considered in the calculation, potentially increasing the SAI for families with business or farm assets8. The SAI formula uses tax data from the “prior-prior year” (e.g., 2023 tax information for the 2025-26 FAFSA)2. The SAI can be negative; the lowest possible SAI is -1500. A negative or zero SAI generally means the student qualifies for the maximum Pell Grant, but it does not result in more aid than the cost of attendance or more than allowed by policy83. Some forms of untaxed income and assets (like distributions from grandparent-owned 529 plans) no longer affect the SAI after recent FAFSA simplifications8. Personal debts such as credit card balances or car loans are not factored into the formula, even though they may affect a family’s perceived ability to pay3. These recent updates ensure families understand why their SAI may differ substantially from what they would have previously calculated under older rules and help set clearer expectations about aid eligibility. Mind Map Expand Key metric for financial aid eligibility Definition Family income Family assets Family size Parents' marital status State of residence Student income and assets Main Inputs CSS Profile colleges Additional Factors SAI replaces Expected Family Contribution (EFC) Recent Changes Student Aid Index (SAI) How does SAI calculation differ for families with multiple children in college? What assets and income are excluded in the new SAI formula? How do changes in business or farm ownership affect financial aid eligibility? this is for a single child to attend 7th grade private school at the grier school which is a boarding school in pennsylvania. there are no other children. do we need to file actual income taxes for 2023 2024 or is there another form that can be filed in lieu of tax returns Tuition & Financial Aid - Grier School https://www.grier.org/join-us/tuition--financial-aid What information will I need to fill out a FAFSA® form? https://studentaid.gov/help/info-needed Apply to Grier https://www.grier.org/join-us/apply-to-grier 28 sources Financial Aid Documentation for The Grier School (PA) 7th Grade Application For private K-12 schools like The Grier School, the financial aid application process typically requires families to submit federal income tax documents, especially IRS Form 1040, as the primary proof of income and financial status. This is consistent with best practices for private school financial aid documentation, where schools request tax returns, W-2s, and sometimes proof of other assets and liabilities to accurately assess financial need141823. Required Tax Documents Most schools, and the Clarity platform (widely used for private school financial aid), specifically request federal income tax returns (Form 1040) as the main documentation of household income for the relevant year, typically the most recently completed tax year (for 2024-2025, likely 2023). Other supporting documents may include W-2 forms, recent pay stubs, and asset statements1423. Are Alternatives Accepted? If you are unable to submit the actual IRS tax return, some schools or platforms may accept alternative documentation in special cases—such as a letter from an employer, pay stubs, or a notarized letter explaining your financial situation. However, these alternatives are rare and typically only accepted if you can show you are not required to file a federal tax return. Some private school platforms (like Clarity and TADS) may require an IRS Verification of Non-Filing Letter if you did not and were not required to file taxes for a given year. In such cases, wage statements or benefit statements and a signed non-filer statement might be acceptable, but this varies by school policy1923. Grier School Specifics While direct mention of Grier School's alternative documentation policy for missing tax returns could not be found, their financial aid page and Clarity's general guidance both strongly imply tax returns are mandatory for financial aid consideration, except in rare, clearly documented exceptions11419. It is recommended to contact the Grier School's financial aid office directly if your family cannot provide the required IRS tax returns, to discuss exceptional circumstances and alternative forms of documentation that might be provisionally accepted. Summary Submitting actual IRS Form 1040 for 2023 will almost certainly be required for financial aid consideration for 2025-2026 admissions to 7th grade at Grier. In rare cases of non-filing, alternative documentation (wage statements, a signed non-filer statement, and/or an IRS Verification of Non-Filing) may be accepted, but only with school approval and proper explanation1923. Always confirm with the school’s financial aid administrator for any exceptions before submitting alternative documents. Grier School uses the Clarity platform for its financial aid process. Clarity has direct integration with the IRS for securely sharing 1040s and W-2s, which means families don't need to scan or upload documents if they give electronic consent—making the process streamlined and secure6. All families seeking need-based aid must re-file a new Clarity application each year to reflect any change in income or tuition, which underscores the importance of up-to-date tax returns for annual reassessment1. Clarity’s methodology scales with the household's circumstance, allowing most families to complete applications within 20–30 minutes, but the requirement for actual tax returns (especially for the most recently completed tax year) remains standard unless explicitly excused by proven tax-exempt status6. There is no evidence in Grier’s financial aid guidelines or within Clarity's FAQs that general alternative documentation (like pay stubs or letters from employers) will be accepted simply for convenience or privacy concerns. Alternatives, such as a non-filing letter, are only relevant if the family is legally exempt from filing a U.S. tax return. In these cases, additional documentation may be requested to verify financial circumstances6. Mind Map Expand Submit IRS Form 1040 Other documents Required Tax Documents Special cases allow alternatives IRS Verification of Non-Filing Are Alternatives Accepted? Tax returns strongly implied mandatory Contact financial aid office for exceptions Grier School Specifics IRS Form 1040 required for 2025-2026 Alternatives may be accepted upon approval Confirm exceptions with financial aid administrator Summary Direct IRS integration Re-file Clarity application annually Duration: 20-30 minutes typically Alternatives not accepted for convenience Clarity Platform Details Financial Aid Documentation for The Grier School What is the Clarity application process timeline for Grier School financial aid? How does foreign income or overseas tax documents impact Grier School financial aid applications? What are the merit-based scholarship requirements at Grier School? which financial aid simulator is best suited for estimating financial aid possible outcomes for grier and 7th grade> or de we need to optimise our own calculator Tuition & Financial Aid - Grier School https://www.grier.org/join-us/tuition--financial-aid Financial Aid Calculator for Private Schools - ThoughtCo https://www.thoughtco.com/private-schools-determine-financial-aid-2774005 Federal Student Aid Estimator https://studentaid.gov/aid-estimator/ 24 sources Financial Aid Estimators for The Grier School 7th Grade Applicants For families applying to The Grier School in Pennsylvania (grades 7–12, boarding and day), there is not a single, nationally standardized, fool-proof financial aid calculator for K-12 private schools, including boarding schools like Grier. Each private school, including Grier, determines financial aid using its own policies, budget, and processes, which are usually managed by third-party platforms such as Clarity (used by The Grier School) or SSS (School and Student Services)126. How Grier Determines Aid Grier School uses Clarity, a widely used financial aid assessment provider for private K-12 schools, to collect detailed financial information and create a Parents’ Financial Statement. This process analyzes income, assets, expenses, family size, and the number of children enrolled in tuition-charging schools1. Clarity then produces an expected family contribution estimate, which Grier’s financial aid committee uses as a guideline—but the final award may differ based on the school's own policies and resources. Simulators/Estimators to Consider Clarity’s estimator (if available): If Grier provides access to a Clarity estimator or demo, this would offer the closest estimate, since it uses the same methodology as the official application. Contact Grier’s financial aid office for access. SSS/NAIS Sample Calculators: The School and Student Services (SSS) form and National Association of Independent Schools (NAIS) offer similar online estimators. If you fill out the SSS Parents’ Financial Statement online, you receive a simulated \"expected family contribution\"—this approach is used by many boarding schools216. General Private School Aid Calculators: These calculators (such as those offered by TADS or the Oaks Academy) can give a rough estimate, but their figures may not align with Grier's exact process, especially given the difference in tuition costs and boarding fees for grades 7–12611. Should You Build a Custom Calculator? Custom calculators are usually unnecessary unless you are a school administrator aiming to tailor the process for a specific population. For parents, using either Grier’s financial aid provider's tools (Clarity) or generic SSS/NAIS simulators will provide guidance on eligibility and award size ranges. Remember, the official application must still be completed for an accurate, final award decision, and awards can differ by school even with identical financial data26. Key Factors Affecting Estimates Grier’s full boarding tuition for 2025–26: $69,900 Financial aid is need-based (based on the difference between tuition and the expected family contribution) Grier also awards some merit scholarships, but these are based on admissions testing and records, not just need1 Each year, a new application must be filed to update financial circumstances12 Summary For 7th grade applicants to The Grier School, the most accurate estimate will come by using the method and financial aid platform (Clarity) adopted by Grier itself. Generic SSS/NAIS calculators are the next-best option if a Clarity estimator is not accessible. Custom tools are rarely needed for families. It's valuable to elaborate how the financial aid formula typically works for private K-12 boarding schools, as referenced by several resources. The standard calculation applied by most private schools—including those using third-party processors like Clarity or SSS—follows this formula: Cost of Attendance (COA) – Estimated Family Contribution (EFC) = Financial Need8. The Cost of Attendance will encompass tuition, room and board, books, and other fees, so for Grier's 2025–26 year, use the $69,900 boarding total as your starting COA1. The EFC is determined based on detailed income, assets (excluding retirement accounts), number of children in tuition-charging schools, family size, and allowances for unusual expenses like medical bills or elder care. Families are generally encouraged to share as much detail as possible for a more accurate assessment8. Some estimates indicate that about 20-25% of private K-12 students receive some level of aid, with average grants at top boarding schools ranging from roughly $17,000 and up, but the spread is large depending on institutional budget and policy28. Additionally, most schools—including Grier—require families to resubmit updated financial paperwork and forms annually to adjust for changes in financial circumstances or tuition rates18. Finally, while there are college financial aid estimators (such as the Federal Student Aid Estimator) and 529-plan calculators, these are designed for higher education and may not account for private K-12 nuances, particularly for boarding schools38. Therefore, tools aimed directly at private K-12, especially those using SSS/Clarity methodology, are the closest approximation you will get without a custom-built, school-specific tool. Mind Map Expand Each school has its own policies Managed by third-party platforms (e.g. Clarity, SSS) No standardized financial aid calculator Uses Clarity for financial assessment How Grier Determines Aid Clarity’s estimator (if available) SSS/NAIS Sample Calculators General Private School Aid Calculators Simulators/Estimators to Consider Custom calculators usually unnecessary for parents Grier's tools and generic simulators are sufficient Official application is necessary for accurate award Should You Build a Custom Calculator? Grier’s full boarding tuition for 2025–26: $69,900 Financial aid is need-based Merit scholarships based on admissions, not need New application required each year Key Factors Affecting Estimates Most accurate estimate via Clarity method Use SSS/NAIS if Clarity not accessible Custom tools rarely needed Summary Cost of Attendance (COA) - EFC = Financial Need EFC based on detailed financial data Share detailed financial information for accuracy Financial Aid Formula 20-25% of K-12 students receive aid Schools require annual financial paperwork updates College financial aid tools are not suitable Additional Insights Financial Aid Estimators for The Grier School 7th Grade Applicants What documentation is required for Clarity or SSS financial aid applications at boarding schools? How does Grier School’s financial aid award compare to similar boarding schools? What expenses are included in the cost of attendance for Grier and similar schools? How does Grier School’s financial aid award compare to similar boarding schools? Tuition & Financial Aid - Grier School https://www.grier.org/join-us/tuition--financial-aid Grier School - BoardingSchools.com https://boardingschools.com/school/grier-school/ Grier School (2025 Profile) - Tyrone, PA https://www.boardingschoolreview.com/grier-school-profile 26 sources Grier School Financial Aid Overview Grier School, a boarding and day school for girls (grades 7-12), offers tuition, room, and board at $69,900 for the 2025-2026 school year. Financial aid at Grier includes both need-based grants and merit-based scholarships. Percentage of Students Receiving Aid: 55% of Grier students receive some form of financial aid. 18% of students receive merit scholarships (this may overlap with those receiving need-based aid)2. Average Financial Aid Award: The average financial aid award is $25,000 per student receiving aid2. Comparison to Similar US Boarding Schools Percentage of Students Receiving Aid The national average for private schools is about 28% of students receiving some form of financial assistance, with some top boarding schools offering aid to 30%-50% of students, and a few elite institutions going above that1516. Grier's 55% is notably higher than the general private school average and aligns with the higher-aid sector of US boarding schools. Other prominent boarding schools for this age range often fall between 25% and 50% of the student body on aid, with only the most generous institutions exceeding 50%1617. Average Award Amount Nationally, the average award per student receiving financial aid is around $11,500 at private schools (all levels), and about $13,830 at the median boarding school (per NAIS data for 2023-2024)1516. For elite or highly resourced US boarding schools, average awards for boarders often range from $20,000 to $45,000. Grier's $25,000 per student sits comfortably in this higher-tier range, indicating it ranks above the typical private school award and in line with better-resourced boarding programs. Context in Co-ed vs. Girls’ Schools Grier is above average in both percentage of students on aid and average award compared to the typical boarding school, regardless of girls-only or co-ed focus. Some of the most competitive East Coast girls’ boarding schools may offer similar or even larger average awards, often due to larger endowments, but Grier's package is competitive in the marketplace for grades 7–12 boarding schools. Summary Table School/Group\t% Receiving Aid\tAvg. Award Grier School\t55%\t$25,000 US Private School (all levels)\t~28%\t$11,500 Median Boarding School (NAIS)\t~30-38%\t$13,830 Highly Generous Boarding Sch.\t30-60%\t$20,000–45,000 Additional Notes Grier also provides need-based grants calculated through a financial aid platform (Clarity), as well as a limited number of merit-based scholarships. All aid is generally renewable with annual review12. Further specifics from additional sources show that Grier offers merit scholarships averaging $20,000, with 18% of students receiving merit aid. Meanwhile, 55% receive any form of aid (need or merit), indicating a substantial overlap but also suggesting a meaningful subset receives only merit-based awards2. Grier's day student tuition and aid offerings are also notable: $28,500 for day tuition with scholarship opportunities available, which expands their aid reach compared to some strictly-boarding peer schools1. On methodology, Grier processes need-based aid applications using the \"Clarity\" financial aid platform, and calculates family contributions annually to adjust grants according to financial circumstances. This annual review principle is common among peer institutions but is a key operational detail for families planning multi-year attendance1. More broadly, for context on US boarding schools with similar enrollment sizes or all-girls focus, there are examples of schools where 40-60% of the student body receives aid, reinforcing that Grier's 55% participation is on the high end—even among aid-forward schools8. At the highest end of elite co-ed or girls' schools, percentage receiving aid can peak above 60% but usually hovers between 40-55%; Grier is thus distinctly competitive in access for middle-class families as well as high-need cases. Finally, while Grier's average award ($25,000) is high, there is variation among schools depending on geographic region, endowment size, and cost of living; some peer schools in high-cost regions or with larger endowments offer higher average awards, but many similarly-priced schools offer smaller average grants, thus placing Grier above the median not just in percentage aided, but in dollar impact for families24. This answer isn't good enough? Try Mixture-of-Agents What are the application requirements for Grier School's need-based financial aid? Which other girls' boarding schools offer comparable or higher financial aid levels? How does Grier School's endowment per student compare to similar US boarding schools? Mixture-of-Agents Search Web"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Source: "},{"type":"link","href":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=aefcb44a-61f3-499d-911a-8356f9fe0dd0","children":[{"text":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=aefcb44a-61f3-499d-911a-8356f9fe0dd0"}]}]}]
